Linear Regression with Python¶

We illustrate (non statistical) linear regression on the Energy efficiency Data Set with StatsModels.

This Data Set is collected from UCI Machine Learning Repository.

" This study looked into assessing the heating load and cooling load requirements of buildings (that is, energy efficiency) as a function of building parameters.

We perform energy analysis using 12 different building shapes simulated in Ecotect. The buildings differ with respect to the glazing area, the glazing area distribution, and the orientation, amongst other parameters. We simulate various settings as functions of the afore-mentioned characteristics to obtain 768 building shapes. The dataset comprises 768 samples and 8 features, aiming to predict two real valued responses.

Attribute Information:

The dataset contains eight attributes (or features, denoted by X1...X8) and two responses (or outcomes, denoted by y1 and y2). The aim is to use the eight features to predict each of the two responses.

Specifically: X1 Relative Compactness X2 Surface Area X3 Wall Area X4 Roof Area X5 Overall Height X6 Orientation X7 Glazing Area X8 Glazing Area Distribution y1 Heating Load y2 Cooling Load "

Note that these data were not collected on real buildings, they are in reality the results of building energy simulation models.

You can find here the article for which the data was produced.

Simple Linear regression¶

We use linear regression to predict Heating_Load (or Cooling Load) from the other variables. We use the formula module from the statsmodels library to define these models.

We start with simple linear regression (with a single feature).

In [ ]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

# model definition :
my_model = smf.ols('Heating_Load ~ Relative_Compactness',data = energ) 

# fit the model on the data (least squares estimation of the coefficients)
res = my_model.fit()

Scikit-learn for linear regression¶

As we can see in the previous procedures, there are many statistical summaries and methods are provided by Statsmodels for the analysis of linear regression, although we have not really exploit these possibilties, by focusing on predictions.

The scikit-learn library, which is totally dedicated to machine learning methods, obviously provides linear regression methods (without statistics). In the following of the labs, we will mainly use scikit-learn library.

Procedures of scikit-learn generally require numpy arrays (not data frames).

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

data = energ.values # np array
X_features = data[:,0:6]
y = data[:,9]

reg = LinearRegression().fit(X_features, y)

reg.score(X_features, y)

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import summary_table
# Get confidence interval information for coefficients
# Data Includes estimates of regression coefficients, standard errors, 
# t-statistics, p-values, and upper and lower bounds for confidence intervals
st, data, ss2 = summary_table(res, alpha=0.05)
ci_low, ci_high = data[:, 4:6].T
predictions = res.get_prediction(X)
mean_values = predictions.predicted_mean
# Plot confidence intervals for coefficients
plt.scatter(mean_values, Y, s = 10, alpha = 0.5, label = "Data values")
plt.plot(mean_values, ci_low, 'r--', label = 'Confidence Interval Lower Bound')
plt.plot(mean_values, ci_high, 'g--', label = 'Confidence Interval Higher Bound')
plt.xlabel('Estimated Values')
plt.ylabel('Observation Values')
plt.title('Confidence Interval Plot')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
